        <h4>Metabolism & Pharmacokinetics</h4>
        <div class="metabolism-details">
          <p><strong>Primary Pathway:</strong> N-demethylation by CYP2B6, CYP3A4 ‚Üí Norpethidine (active, toxic)</p>
          <p><strong>Secondary Pathway:</strong> Hydrolysis ‚Üí Pethidinic acid (inactive)</p>
          <p><strong>Half-life:</strong> 3-5 hours (parent drug), 8-21 hours (norpethidine)</p>
          <p><strong>Bioavailability:</strong> ~50% oral (high first-pass metabolism)</p>
          <p><strong>Peak plasma:</strong> 1-2 hours after oral dose</p>
          <p><strong>Elimination:</strong> Primarily renal (norpethidine accumulates in kidney disease)</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Norpethidine Toxicity</h4>
        <div class="neurotoxicity-info">
          <p><strong>Mechanism:</strong> Norpethidine is a CNS stimulant that blocks sodium channels and has pro-convulsant properties</p>
          <p><strong>Accumulation:</strong> Half-life 2-3 times longer than parent drug, accumulates with repeated dosing</p>
          <p><strong>Toxicity:</strong> Tremor, muscle twitches, multifocal myoclonus, seizures</p>
          <p><strong>Risk factors:</strong> Renal impairment, elderly age, high doses, prolonged use</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Unique Pharmacological Properties</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Serotonergic activity:</strong> Risk of serotonin syndrome when combined with SSRIs/MAOIs</li>
          <li><strong>Local anesthetic:</strong> Sodium channel blockade provides additional analgesic properties</li>
          <li><strong>Short duration:</strong> Shortest-acting of the traditional opioids</li>
          <li><strong>Poor sublingual/rectal absorption:</strong> Oral or injection routes preferred</li>
          <li><strong>No active metabolites:</strong> Except norpethidine, which is problematic rather than beneficial</li>
        </ul>
